    "best_read": "Catch in the shooting pocket and rise. The closeout is short and under control — the shot is open before his hands get up.",
    "acceptable_reads": [
      "Rip and drive baseline if the defender is sprinting past — produces a layup or kickout, but loses the clean catch-and-shoot."
    ],
    "bad_reads": [
      "Pass back to the point — gives up the open look and resets the defense.",
      "Hold and pump fake — the defender closes the cushion and contests."
    ],
    "common_miss_reason": "Loyalty to the dribble. Wings catch and put the ball on the floor by reflex even when the defender's cushion already gives them the shot.",
    "why_best_read_works": "The defender was helping one pass away. Closing out from the help position cannot beat the ball — a catch in the shooting pocket forces the contest before his hands are up. The shot is open precisely because the defender bet on the help.",
    "decoder_teaching_point": "On the catch, read the closeout. Short and under control means his cushion is yours — shoot before his hands are up.",
    "lesson_connection": "advantage-or-reset",
    "explanation_md": "**Advantage or Reset — fewer hints.** The hip arrow is gone, but the read is the same. Look at his feet and the cushion in front of you. If his feet are still pointed at the ball and his hands aren't up, he is short — catch and shoot. If he flies past you, drive. If he is set, reset. Real defenders don't paint arrows on themselves; read the body.",
    "feedback": {
      "correct": "Good read. No arrow — you read his feet and the cushion, and shot before his hands were up.",
      "partial": "A drive can work against a flying closeout. This one was short and under control — the shot was the cleaner read.",
      "wrong": "Read his feet and his cushion. If the closeout is short, the shot is open. Catch and shoot."
    },
